ce:section.ce:para:
Using green one-step microwave-assisted pyrolysis in a domestic microwave oven, the water-soluble N,S-CDs were produced within a very short time (just 60s) with high production yield of 64.38 wt%. The highly fluorescent N,S-CDs were made utilizing readily accessible starting materials and straightforward process, with CA; source of carbon and TSC; nitrogen/sulfur dopant (Scheme 1
                        ). The optical image of the N,S-CDs solution under normal light, and UV light is shown in Fig. S1. The prepared N,S-CDs displayed blue fluorescence when exposed to UV light and exhibited a longstanding fluorescence stability for two weeks. TEM images (Fig. 1
                        A) reveal that the prepared CDs were homogeneously distributed quasispherical particles without any apparent aggregation and had a narrow size range of 1–5 nm. The lattice fringes within the particles, shown in HRTEM images (Fig. 1B), indicate the crystallinity of the N,S-CDs with the lattice spacing was found to be 0.20 nm corresponding to the (101) plane of graphitic crystal structure [40,41]. The crystallinity was further confirmed by the selected area electron diffraction (SAED) pattern (Fig. 1C). Elemental analysis was accomplished by EDX, to ascertain the composition of the N,S-CDs, and demonstrated that the N,S-CDs were predominantly made up of C (39.94%), O (23.03%), N (28.56%), and S (8.47%) revealing that a high doping level was achieved (Fig. S2). The surface groups were examined using FT-IR (Fig. 2
                        ) and revealed the following peaks (cm−1): N–H (3567 and 3374), O–H (3203), CN (2062), CO (1715), CC (1620), CN/NN (1497), CS (1417), C–N/SO (1313) and C–O/N–N (1077). The UV spectrum (Fig. 3
                        A) was recorded to examine the optical characteristics of the CDs and revealed that they have two peaks at 240 nm and 308 nm, corresponding to the π-π∗/n-π∗ transitions [42,43]. The emission of synthesized CDs displayed excitation dependency across 300–390 nm range (Fig. 3B). The maximum fluorescence emission occurred at 430 nm after excitation at 350 nm (quantum yield of 10.7%). The fluorescence of the N,S-CDs was directly proportional to its concentration in the range of 0.01–0.1 mg mL−1 (Fig. S3). The N,S-CDs fluorescence was markedly quenched upon adding Cu2+ ions, which could then be restored by introduction of ETD to the N,S-CDs-Cu2+ system. Accordingly, new Cu2+ and ETD detection sensor based on a fluorescence turn off-on strategy was developed.

The system fluorescence gradually switched on by addition of increasing concentrations of ETD (Fig. 9
                        ). A plot of the fluorescence recovery (F–F
                        0) against ETD concentration showed linearity in the range of 30–210 μM with r2 = 0.993; where the regression equation was y = 0.454x - 1.493 and the DL was 8.592 μM (Table 1). To ensure the reliability of the sensor for practical application, possible interfering materials such as lactose, maltose, HPMC, mannitol, dextrin, CA and tartaric acid were utilized to test the selectivity of the N,S-CDs-Cu2+ system towards ETD (Fig. 8B). The developed sensing system could successfully and selectively detect ETD without interference from common excipients in pharmaceutical formulations.
